&lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/cybernetic-postliberalism/terms/genre-calibration/>
  rdf:type schema:Article ;
  schema:url &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/cybernetic-postliberalism/terms/genre-calibration/> ;
  schema:name "Genre calibration" ;
  schema:description "The continuous, distributed tuning by which expectations are adjusted so that structural crisis is experienced as personal narrative. The mechanism synthesizes three theoretical bodies: Berlant's account of genre as structure of anticipation (genre is not applied to events after the fact — it shapes what events *are*), Ahmed's account of how affects circulate, accumulate stickiness, and orient bodies toward normative objects within those genres, and Wiener's cybernetic account of feedback that maintains stability without central coordination. The same job loss is calibrated as 'pivot' (self-help genre, opportunity), 'wound' (therapeutic genre, requiring healing), or 'exploitation' (activist genre, evidence of structural failure); the recession is the same recession; what changes is the genre, and the calibration is what tunes which genre takes hold for which subject under which conditions." ;
  schema:datePublished "2026-03-06" ;
  schema:dateModified "2026-03-06" ;
  emsenn:Contrastswith "genre-fixity" , "ideological-determination" , "command-control" ;
  schema:about &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/cybernetic-postliberalism/terms/genre-calibration/> ;
